## Global Rules (All Apps)
 
### Architecture & Platform Boundaries
- Treat every app as a TelemetryOS application with two strict mount points:
  - `/render` — viewer-facing digital signage UI
  - `/settings` — Studio/admin configuration UI
- `/render` and `/settings` must be separate entry components.
- Do not share UI components directly between Render and Settings.
- Shared logic must live in typed config models, utilities, or constants.
- Assume a digital signage runtime:
  - large screens
  - long viewing distance
  - no user interaction
- Never add viewer-side interactions (buttons, hover states, scrolling) in `/render`.
- Use instance storage as the single source of truth for configuration.
- Render must subscribe to instance storage updates; never read Settings UI state directly.
 
### Responsive Scaling & Sizing
- Use **REM units only** for all sizing, spacing, and typography in `/render`.
- Apply UI scaling (e.g. `useUiScaleToSetRem`) at the root of the Render app.
- Typography minimums for signage:
  - Primary text: ≥ 6rem
  - Secondary text: ≥ 3rem
  - Tertiary text: ≥ 1.5rem
- Maintain safe zones:
  - minimum 3rem padding from all edges
- Layouts must adapt to all standard TelemetryOS shapes:
  - Landscape
  - Portrait
  - Large Square
  - Small Square
  - Landscape Bar
  - Portrait Bar
  - Chiron Banner
  - Skyscraper
- Respect content priority levels (P1, P2, P3) when space is constrained.
 
### Componentization & Code Structure
- Each distinct feature must be its own component.
- Keep view files (`Render.tsx`, `Settings.tsx`) thin and declarative.
- Call SDK `configure(...)` exactly once at the app entry point.
- Centralize:
  - storage keys
  - shared types
  - constants
- Parsing, formatting, and data normalization must live in `utils/`, never inside components.
 
### Visual Rules for Digital Signage
- Each layout must have a single clear focal point.
- Avoid dense multi-column layouts unless the zone is very large.
- Maintain high contrast for readability.
- If using image or video backgrounds, always apply an overlay for legibility.
- Assume background modes may include:
  - solid
  - gradient
  - image
  - video
 
### Settings UI Constraints
- Only use supported Settings primitives:
  - text input
  - textarea
  - select/dropdown
  - slider
  - color picker
  - switch / checkbox / radio
  - section heading
  - divider
  - bordered box
  - media picker
  - button
- Do not implement custom widgets, tabs, accordions, or rich editors.
 
### Reliability & Runtime Behavior
- Prefer fail-soft rendering.
- If part of the data fails, render remaining valid content.
- Network requests must use platform-safe mechanisms.
- Background workers must be DOM-free.
- Render must never block on network requests.
 
 
